  "prompt": "College and NCAA Football: (NFL) In overtime, is the kicking team allowed to do an onside kick and if successful does the other team get the ball afterwards?",
  "response": "In the NFL, during overtime, the kicking team is allowed to attempt an onside kick. If the kicking team successfully recovers the onside kick, they retain possession of the ball and have the opportunity to continue their drive. The other team does not get the ball afterward unless they either force a turnover or the kicking team fails to advance the ball and turns it over on downs, or if the kicking team scores a touchdown or a field goal, after which the game would be over.\n\nIt's worth noting that if the kicking team does not recover the onside kick, then the receiving team takes over the ball at the spot of the recovery. So, in summary, the kicking team can attempt an onside kick in overtime, and if they recover it, they keep the ball.",
